'''Jill Tracy Jacobs Biden''' (born June 5, 1951) is an American [[educator]] and, as the wife of [[Vice President of the United States]] [[Joe Biden]], the [[Wife of the Vice President of the United States|Second Lady of the United States]].

She was born in [[Hammonton, New Jersey]] and grew up in [[Willow Grove, Pennsylvania]].  She graduated with a bachelor's degree from the [[University of Delaware]].  She married Joe Biden in 1977.  They had a daughter together in 1981 as well as two sons from his first marriage.  She taught English and reading in high schools for 13 years, and earned master's degrees from [[West Chester University]] and [[Villanova University]].  She also taught emotionally disturbed adolescents at a psychiatric hospital.  From 1993 to 2008 she was an English and writing instructor at [[Delaware Technical & Community College]].  She received a doctorate degree from the University of Delaware in 2007.

She is the founder of the Biden Breast Health Initiative non-profit organization, co-founded the Book Buddies program, and is active in Delaware Boots on the Ground.  She participated in her husband's presidential and vice-presidential campaigns while continuing to teach at the same time.  As of 2009, she is an [[adjunct professor]] of English at [[Northern Virginia Community College]], and she is thought to be the first Second Lady to hold a paying job while her husband is Vice President.

==Early life==
Jill Tracy Jacobs was born in [[Hammonton, New Jersey]].<ref name="pi082708"/> After moving several times while very young, she and her four younger sisters spent the majority of their childhood in [[Willow Grove, Pennsylvania]].<ref name="tnj100608"/><ref name="progressohio.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.progressohio.org/page/community/post/daveharding/CHBm|title=Meet Dr. Jill Biden|accessdate=2008-08-24|publisher=Progress Ohio.org}}</ref> Her father, Donald C. Jacobs (c.1927<U+2013>1999),<ref name="pi060999"/> was a [[bank teller]] who became head of a [[savings and loan]] in [[Chestnut Hill, Pennsylvania]].<ref name="vogue1108">{{cite news | url=http://www.style.com/vogue/feature/2008_Nov_Jill_Biden/ | title=All the Vice-President's Women | author=Van Meter, Jonathan | publisher=''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' as presented on Style.com | date=November 2008 | accessdate=2008-12-29}}</ref>  His family name had originally been Giacoppa before being anglicized.<ref name="vogue1108"/>  Her mother, Bonny Jean Jacobs (c.1930<U+2013>2008),<ref name="tnj100608">{{cite news | url=http://search.delawareonline.com/sp?skin=100&aff=1117&keywords=Joe+Biden%27s+mother-in-law+dies+at+78&pubDate=180&author= | title=Joe Biden's mother-in-law dies at 78 | author=Nathans, Aaron | publisher=''[[The News Journal]]'' | date=2008-10-06 | accessdate=2009-02-04 | format=fee required}}</ref> was a [[homemaker]].<ref name="pi060999">{{cite news | url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PI&s_site=philly&p_multi=PI&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB5CE453393F8F9&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM | title=Donald C. Jacobs, 72 | publisher=''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' | date=1999-06-09 | accessdate=2008-09-19}}</ref> 
The family was not particularly religious, but in ninth grade, Jacobs independently took classes in order to join the [[Presbyterian church]].<ref name="vogue1108"/>

Always intending to have her own career, Jacobs began working at age 15, including waitressing at the [[Jersey shore]].<ref name="vogue1108"/><ref name="nyt082508">{{cite news | url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/25/us/politics/25wife.html | title=Jill Biden Heads Toward Life in the Spotlight | author=Seelye, Katharine Q. | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=2008-08-24 | accessdate=2008-08-25}}</ref>  She attended [[Upper Moreland High School]], where she was somewhat rebellious and enjoyed social life, but always liked English class.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.phillyburbs.com/pb-dyn/news/113-11072008-1617762.html | title=Jill Biden getting attention | author=Tasker, Annie | publisher=''Bucks County Courier Times'' | date=2008-11-07 | accessdate=2008-11-07}}</ref> She graduated in 1969.<ref name="bcct082808">{{cite news | url=http://www.phillyburbs.com/pb-dyn/news/111-08282008-1582679.html | title=Upper Moreland grad Jill Biden in campaign limelight | author=Cosentino, Dom | publisher=''Bucks County Courier Times'' | date=2008-08-28 | accessdate=2008-08-28}}</ref>

==Education and career, marriage and family==
Jacobs enrolled in a junior college in Pennsylvania to study [[fashion merchandising]], but soon found it unsatisfying.<ref name="vogue1108"/>  She married someone she had been dating following high school.<ref name="vogue1108"/>  She and her husband enrolled in the [[University of Delaware]], where she declared English as her major.<ref name="vogue1108"/>  After two years the couple grew apart, divorcing while she was a junior at Delaware.<ref name="vogue1108"/>  She then took a year off from college and did some [[model (person)|modelling]] work for a local agency in Wilmington.<ref name="vogue1108"/>  Subsequently, she returned to college, meeting Joe Biden while a senior at Delaware in March 1975.<ref name="nyt082508"/>  They met on a blind date set up by Joe's brother, though it turned out that Biden had unknowingly fancied her, having seen her in a local advertisement.<ref name="nyt082508"/> She graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from the [[University of Delaware]] later in 1975.<ref name="dtcc">{{cite web|url=http://www.dtcc.edu/catalog/pdf/personnel.pdf|title=Administrative, Instructional, and Student Services Personnel|accessdate=2008-08-23|publisher=[[Delaware Technical & Community College]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.udel.edu/udaily/2009/nov/election110508.html | title=University of Delaware plays major role in national election | author=Thomas, Neil | publisher=[[University of Delaware]] | date=2008-11-05 | accessdate=2009-01-24}}</ref> She began her career teaching high school English.<ref name="nyt082508"/> 

Jill Jacobs and Joe Biden were married on June 17, 1977 at the Chapel at the [[United Nations]] in [[New York City]], about five years after Joe Biden's first wife and infant daughter died in a car accident,<ref name="pi082708"/> and after several proposals where she hesitated before accepting the commitment of raising his two young sons who survived the accident.<ref name="vogue1108"/>  She continued to teach and then, while pregnant, received a [[Master of Education]] with a specialty in Reading from [[West Chester University]] in 1981.<ref name="vogue1108"/><ref>{{cite news | url=http://media.www.wcuquad.com/media/storage/paper676/news/2008/10/20/News/The-Quad.Talks.With.Jill.Biden-3495422.shtml | title=The Quad talks with Jill Biden | author=Stern, Frank | publisher=''The Quad'' | date=2008-10-20 | accessdate=2008-12-29}}</ref><ref name="dtcc"/> The Bidens' daughter Ashley Blazer was born on June 8, 1981,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/apps/pbcs.dll/section?Category=caucus&template=detail&candidate=biden | title=Iowa Caucuses '08: Joe Biden: Timeline | publisher=''[[The Des Moines Register]]'' | accessdate=2009-02-04}}</ref> and Jill stopped working for two years while raising the three children.<ref name="nj031907">{{cite news | url=http://search.delawareonline.com/sp?skin=100&aff=1117&keywords=%22It%20was%20Joe,%20the%20boys,%20and%20the%20state%20of%20Delaware%22 | title=Determined to stay in school | author=Hale, Charlotte | publisher=''[[The News Journal]]'' | date=2007-03-19 | accessdate=2008-08-29 | format=fee required}}</ref>

She then returned to work, teaching English, acting as a reading specialist, and teaching history to emotionally disturbed students.<ref name="nyt082508"/> She also worked as a teacher in the adolescent program at the Rockford Center [[psychiatric hospital]] for five years in the 1980s.<ref name="pi082708"/><ref name="vogue1108"/> In 1987, Biden received a [[Master of Arts]] in English from [[Villanova University]].<ref name="pi082708">{{cite news | url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/20080827_Colleagues_see_a_caring__giving_Jill_Biden.html | title=Colleagues see a caring, giving Jill Biden | author=Farrell, Joelle | publisher=''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' | date=2008-08-27 | accessdate=2008-08-28}}</ref><ref name="dtcc"/>  During [[Joe Biden presidential campaign, 1988|her husband's 1988 bid for the Presidency]], she said she would continue her job of teaching emotionally disturbed children even if she became [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]].<ref name="caroli">{{cite book | last=Caroli | first=Betty Boyd | title=First Ladies: From Martha Washington to Laura Bush | publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] | year=2003 | isbn=0-195-16676-0 | pages=297}}</ref>  In all, she spent 13 years teaching in public high school,<ref name="nyt082508"/> including 3 years at [[Claymont High School (Delaware)|Claymont High School]].<ref name="vogue1108"/>

From 1993 through 2008, Biden was an instructor at the Stanton/Wilmington campus of [[Delaware Technical & Community College]].<ref name="dtcc"/><ref name="wapo-cc"/><ref name="npr010108"/>  There she taught [[Composition studies|English composition]] and [[Remedial education|remedial writing]], with an emphasis on instilling confidence in students.<ref name="lat082708">{{cite news | url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/washingtondc/la-na-jill27-2008aug27,0,4471572.story | title=Jill Biden has a low-key appeal | author=Gaouette, Nicole | publisher=''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' | date=2008-08-27 | accessdate=2008-08-28}}</ref><ref name="wapo-cc"/> She has said of teaching at a community college, "I feel like I can make a greater difference in their lives. I just love that population. It just feels really comfortable to me. I love the women who are coming back to school and getting their degrees, because they're so focused."<ref name="wapo-cc">{{cite news | url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/10/22/AR2008102203657.html | title=Campaign Curriculum | author=[[Libby Copeland|Copeland, Libby]] | publisher=''[[The Washington Post]]'' | date=2008-10-23 | accessdate=2008-10-25}}</ref>

Biden is the president of the Biden Breast Health Initiative, a non-profit organization begun in 1993 that provides educational breast health awareness programs free of charge to schools and other groups in the state of Delaware.<ref>{{cite news |first=Nancy |last=Churnin |title=Obama's VP pick, Joe Biden, could heighten [[breast cancer]] awareness |url=http://fitnessblog.dallasnews.com/archives/2008/08/expect-more-breast-cancer-awar.html |work=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |date=August 23, 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bidenbreasthealthinitiative.org/aboutus.html |title=About Us |publisher=Biden Breast Health Initiative|accessdate=2009-02-04}}</ref>  In the following 15 years, the organization informed more than 7,000 high school girls about proper breast health.<ref name="wh-bio"/>  In 2007, Biden helped found Book Buddies, which provides books for low-income children,<ref name="wh-bio"/> and has been very active in Delaware Boots on the Ground, an organization that supports military families.<ref name="lat082708"/>  She runs five miles, five times a week, and has run in the [[Marine Corps Marathon]].<ref name="nyt082508"/>

Biden later returned to school for her doctorate degree, studying under her birth name, Jill Jacobs.<ref name="nj031907"/> In January 2007, at age 55, she received a [[Doctor of Education]] in [[educational leadership]] from the University of Delaware.<ref name="pi082708"/><ref name="dissert"/><ref name="wh-bio">{{cite web | url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/administration/jill_biden/ | title=Dr. Jill Biden | publisher=[[The White House]] | accessdate=2009-01-22}}</ref><ref name="lat020209"/>  Her dissertation ''Student Retention at the Community College: Meeting Students' Needs'' was published under the name Jill Jacobs-Biden.<ref name="dissert">{{cite book | last=Jacobs-Biden | first=Jill | title=Student Retention at the Community College: Meeting Students' Needs | publisher=[[University of Delaware]] | year=2006 | url=http://proquest.umi.com/pqdlink?did=1251897961&Fmt=7&clientId=79356&RQT=309&VName=PQD&cfc=1e=PQD&cfc=1|format=fee required, partial preview available}}</ref>

==2008 Presidential campaigns==
Following her strong dismay at [[George W. Bush presidential campaign, 2004|George W. Bush's reelection in 2004]], she urged her husband to run again for President.<ref name="wapo-cc"/><ref name="npr010108"/> During [[Joe Biden presidential campaign, 2008|Joe Biden's 2008 campaign to be the Democratic nominee]], she continued to teach during the week and would join him for campaigning on weekends.<ref name="npr010108"/> She said that she would have taken an activist role in addressing education as her chief focus of concern as a potential First Lady.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0,28804,1660946_1661078,00.html | title=Democrat Candidate Spouses: Jill Biden | publisher=''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' | accessdate=2008-08-23}}</ref> She also said that she was basically apolitical and would not seek inclusion in Cabinet meetings.<ref name="npr010108">{{cite news | url=http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=17764989 | title=Presidential Candidates' Spouses: Jill Biden | author=Norris, Michelle | work=[[All Things Considered]] | publisher=[[NPR]] | date=2008-01-01 | accessdate=2008-08-26}}</ref>

Once her husband was selected to be Democratic presidential nominee [[Barack Obama]]'s running mate, she began campaigning again.
She wore a [[Blue Star Mothers Club]] pin in recognition of [[Beau Biden]]'s deployment to [[Iraq war|Iraq]].<ref name="wapo-cc"/>  She was not a polished political speaker, but was able to establish a connection with the audience.<ref name="wapo-cc"/> She also made some joint appearances with [[Michelle Obama]].<ref name="pol112708">{{cite news | url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1108/16040.html | title=Jill Biden: Untraditional, unapologetic | author=Lee, Carol E. | publisher=''[[The Politico]]'' | date=2008-11-27 | accessdate=2008-11-28}}</ref>  Throughout the time her husband was running for vice president, Jill Biden continued to teach four days a week at Delaware Technical & Community College during the Fall 2008 semester, and then campaigned over the long weekend, while grading class papers on the campaign bus.<ref name="tnj100608"/><ref name="wapo-cc"/><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.reuters.com/article/joeBiden/idUSN0143167020081103 | title=Jill Biden, teacher who avoids 'Washington scene' | author=Pleming, Sue | publisher=[[Reuters]] | date=2008-11-03 | accessdate=2008-11-06}}</ref>

==Second Lady of the United States==
[[File:20090120 Jill and Joe Biden at Homestates Ball.JPG|thumb|right|upright|Jill and Joe Biden dancing at the [[Barack Obama 2009 presidential inauguration#Inaugural balls|President Obama Home States Ball]], January 20, 2009.]]
Despite moving to [[Number One Observatory Circle|the vice presidential residence in Washington]] as [[Second Lady of the United States]], Biden intended to keep teaching at a Washington-area community college, and several of them recruited her.<ref name="nydn122808">{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/2008/12/27/2008-12-27_from_a_blind_date_to_second_lady_jill_bi.html?page=0 | title=From a blind date to second lady, Jill Biden's coming into her own | author=Evans, Heidi | publisher=''[[New York Daily News]]'' | date=2008-12-28 | accessdate=2009-01-03}}</ref><ref name="nyt112108">{{cite news | url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/23/fashion/23biden.html | title=<U+2018>Amtrak Joe<U+2019> No More | author=Bosman, Julie | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=2008-11-21 | accessdate=2008-11-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/reliable-source/2009/01/campuses_crusade_to_secure_pro.html | title=Campuses Crusade to Secure Prof. Biden | publisher=''[[The Washington Post]]'' | date=2009-01-16 | accessdate=2009-01-16}}</ref>  In January 2009, she began teaching two English courses as an [[adjunct professor]] at the Alexandria campus of [[Northern Virginia Community College]], the second-largest community college in the nation.<ref name="wapo012709">{{cite news | url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/44/2009/01/27/jill_biden_returns_to_the_clas.html?hpid=news-col-blog | title=Jill Biden Returns to the Classroom | author=Rucker, Philip | publisher=''[[The Washington Post]]'' | date=2009-01-27 | accessdate=2009-01-27}}</ref><ref name="lat020209"/>  It has been rare for Second Ladies to work while their spouses serve as Vice President,<ref name="pol112708"/><ref name="nyt112108"/> and Biden is thought to be the first Second Lady to hold a paying job while her husband is Vice President.<ref name="lat020209">{{cite news | url=http://www.latimes.com/news/politics/la-na-dr-jill-biden2-2009feb02,0,7421785.story | title=Jill Biden, doctor of education, is back in class | author=Abcarian, Robin | publisher=''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' | date=2009-02-02 | accessdate=2009-02-02}}</ref>  Biden planned to be a public advocate for the importance of community colleges and to advise the Obama administration on issues related to them.<ref name="wapo012709"/>  In White House announcements, she is referred to as "Dr. Jill Biden".<ref name="lat020209"/>

Catherine Russell, a former adviser to the [[Senate Foreign Relations Committee]], was named Biden's chief-of-staff for her Second Lady role,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/the-trail/2008/11/25/biden_beefs_up_staff.html | title=Biden Beefs Up Staff | author=Rucker, Philip | publisher=''[[The Washington Post]]'' | accessdate=2008-12-02 | date=2008-11-25}}</ref> while Courtney O<U+2019>Donnell, a former spokesperson for [[Howard Dean]] and [[Elizabeth Edwards]], was named her communications director.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.stltoday.com/blogzone/political-fix/political-fix/2009/01/st-louis-native-will-speak-for-jill-biden/ | title=St. Louis native will speak for Jill Biden | author=Wagman, Jake | publisher=''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' | date=2009-01-06 | accessdate=2009-01-06}}</ref>

On the ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' just before the inauguration, Jill Biden said that Obama had offered her husband either the Vice-Presidency or the position of [[United States Secretary of State|U.S. Secretary of State]].<ref name="slip">{{Cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/national/37849314.html?elr=KArksLckD8EQDUoaEyqyP4O:DW3ckUiD3aPc:_Yyc:aUnciaec8O7EyUsI|title=Jill Biden lets slip secret about Joe|accessdate=January 20 2009|dateformat=mdy|publisher=Minneapolis Star Tribune|year=January 19, 2009|author=Minneapolis Star Tribune}}</ref><ref name="nyt011909">{{cite news | url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/01/19/the-bidens-on-oprah/ | title=The Bidens on Oprah | author=Seelye, Katharine Q. | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=2009-01-19 | accessdate=2009-01-20}}</ref> However, Joe Biden's spokesperson stated that Biden had only been offered one job by Obama.<ref name="nyt011909"/>
